<br>
Do you seriously think it is the right of USA to walk into any country where it disagrees with how the government runs the place?<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
The issues that began the conflict stemmed from the inspectors not being given complete, unrestricted co-operation with the inspections.  There are a few different views floating around about this topic, its not  really what my point is.<br>
<br>
Basically, one side believed Saddam was hiding banned equipment and weapons.  (banned internationally and also from the sanctions from his stint in Kuwait)  The other side did not believe it, however agreed to steps to ensure it was the case.  Through several steps taken through the U.N. and some resulotions to attempt to make things  easier and faster for the &quot;disarmarment&quot; of iraq, there were several altematems (like i can spell) placed into the agreements.  What happened in the end was both sides painted themselves into a corner.  Neither side willing to back down.<br>
<br>
In the end, conflict happened.  It didn't happen because the USA &quot;disagrees with how the government runs the place.&quot;.  It happened for other reasons.  Other more contraversial reasons.  I don't think you could find a single member of the U.N. other than the Iraqi ambassador to the U.N. that supports how the Saddam regime ran the place.<br>
